  url = {https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/mbe.12322},
  urldate = {2025-09-03},
  abstract = {ABSTRACT                            Classrooms are noisy: when children are engaged in solo work, they also hear background babble, noise from outdoor, and people moving around. Few studies investigating the effects of noise on academic tasks use naturalistic stimuli. Questions also remain regarding why some children are more impaired by noise than others. This study compared primary school children's performance at three academic tasks (text recall, reading comprehension, mathematics) in silence, and while hearing irrelevant verbal noise (storytelling,               n               ~=~33) or mixed noise (outdoor noise, movement, babble,               n               ~=~31). We found that noise does not impair overall performance. Children might use compensatory strategies (e.g., re‐reading) to reach the same level of performance in silence and noise. Individual differences in selective attention and working memory were not related to the impact of noise, with one exception: children with lower working memory were more impaired by noise when doing mathematics. Replication on a larger sample is needed.                        ,              LAY ABSTRACT             We tested if verbal noise (hearing a story) and mixed noise (outdoor noise, movement, babble) impaired primary school children's capacity to remember and understand texts and to perform well in mathematics. On average, performance was not worse in noise compared to silence. The effect of noise was not related to children's selective attention nor working memory with one exception: children with lower working memory were more impaired when doing maths.},
  langid = {english},
